# Personal Data Protection Act (Singapore)

## No. 26 of 2012

### Chapter 1 - Preliminary

#### 1. Short title and commencement

This Act may be cited as the Personal Data Protection Act 2012 and shall come into operation on such date as the Minister may, by notification in the Gazette, appoint.

#### 2. Interpretation

In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires —

'agency' means a Ministry or department of the Government, or any authority, body or statutory board, established by or under any written law;

'consent' means agreement to the collection, use or disclosure of personal data about an individual in the circumstances set out in this Act;

'controller' means an organisation that makes decisions about the purposes for and the manner in which personal data is processed;

'data intermediary' means an organisation that processes personal data on behalf of another organisation but does not include an employee of an organisation who processes personal data in the course of his employment;

'personal data' means data, whether true or not, about an individual who can be identified from that data; if the data is in the possession of or is under the control of an organisation, the individual can be identified from the data in combination with other data in the possession of or under the control of the organisation and accessible by or on behalf of the organisation;

'processing', in relation to any data, means doing any operation or set of operations on the data, whether or not by automated means, including —
(a) recording;
(b) holding;
(c) organising;
(d) adapting or altering;
(e) retrieving;
(f) consulting;
(g) using;
(h) disclosing;
(i) erasing;
(j) destroying;
(k) protecting;
(l) securing;
(m) anonymising;
(n) combining;
(o) linking;
(p) transferring;
(q) making available;
(r) restoring;
(s) recovering;
(t) copying;
(u) modifying;
(v) publishing;
(w) disseminating;
(x) transmitting;
(y) sending;
(z) forwarding;
(aa) routing;
(bb) broadcasting;
(cc) relaying;
(dd) carrying; or
(ee) delivering.

### Chapter 2 - Data Protection Framework

#### 3. Scope of Act

This Act governs the collection, use, disclosure and care of personal data by organisations in a manner that recognises both the rights of individuals to protect their personal data and the needs of organisations to collect, use or disclose personal data for purposes that a reasonable person would consider appropriate in the circumstances.

#### 4. Obligation to protect personal data

An organisation shall protect personal data in its possession or under its control by making reasonable security arrangements to prevent unauthorised access, collection, use, disclosure, copying, modification, disposal or other similar risks.

#### 5. Consent obligation

An organisation may collect, use or disclose personal data about an individual only if it has obtained the individual's consent to such collection, use or disclosure, unless the collection, use or disclosure is —
(a) pursuant to the common law rights or duties of the organisation; or
(b) permitted under the provisions of any written law.

#### 6. Purpose limitation

An organisation shall not collect, use or disclose personal data about an individual for any purpose unless such collection, use or disclosure is with the individual's consent and is for a purpose within the scope of the purpose or purposes for which the consent was given.

#### 7. Notification of purpose

An organisation shall inform an individual of the purposes for which personal data about the individual is collected, used or disclosed by the organisation before or at the time of, or as soon as practicable after, the data is collected, used or disclosed.

# ASEAN Framework Agreement on Services - Chapter on Financial Services

## AFAS - Financial Services Chapter

### Article 1 - Definitions

For the purposes of this Chapter:

'Financial service' means any service of a financial nature offered by a financial service supplier of a Member State. This includes:

(a) All insurance and insurance-related services including:
(i) Life and non-life insurance;
(ii) Reinsurance and retrocession;
(iii) Insurance intermediation such as brokerage and agency;
(iv) Services auxiliary to insurance such as consultancy, actuarial, risk assessment, and claim settlement;

(b) All banking and other financial services (excluding insurance) including:
(i) Acceptance of deposits and other repayable funds from the public;
(ii) Lending of all types including consumer credit, mortgage credit, factoring and financing of commercial transactions;
(iii) Financial leasing;
(iv) Payment and money transmission services;
(v) Guarantees and commitments;
(vi) Trading for own account or for accounts of customers in money market instruments, foreign exchange, derivative products, exchange and interest rate instruments, transferable securities, and commodities;
(vii) Participation in securities issues and provision of investment services;
(viii) Money management;
(ix) Financial advice;
(x) Custodial and related services;
(xi) Settlement and clearing services for financial assets;
(xii) Providing references and credit reporting;
(xiii) Sale of payment instruments such as credit cards and traveler's cheques;

'Financial service supplier' means any natural or legal person of a Member State that supplies or seeks to supply a financial service.

'Member State' means Brunei Darussalam, Cambodia, Indonesia, Lao PDR, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam.

### Article 2 - Scope of Application

This Chapter applies to measures by Member States affecting the supply of financial services by financial service suppliers of another Member State.

This Chapter does not apply to:

(a) Services supplied in the exercise of governmental authority;
(b) Financial services provided by central banks or monetary authorities;
(c) Government procurement of financial services.

### Article 3 - Market Access

Each Member State shall permit financial service suppliers of any other Member State to establish commercial presence in its territory under the terms and conditions set forth in its Schedule.

Market access shall be granted without limitation as to the total value of transactions, the number of operations, or the total quantity of output.

### Article 4 - National Treatment

Each Member State shall accord to financial service suppliers of any other Member State treatment no less favorable than that it accords to its own financial service suppliers.

### Article 5 - Prudential Measures

Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to prevent a Member State from maintaining or adopting prudential measures for the protection of investors, depositors, policyholders, or the financial system.

### Article 6 - New Obligations

Member States agree to progressively liberalize trade in financial services through successive rounds of negotiations and commitments.
